AGI - "Papa Francesco> has been a luminous witness of a Church > that bends with tenderness towards those who are wounded and heals with the balm of mercy". Thus Cardinal Pietro Parolin>, former Secretary of State, in the homily of the mass of the second day of the Novendials. "He reminded us that there can be no peace without the recognition of the other, without the attention to those who are weaker and, above all, there can never be peace if we do not learn to forgive each other, using among us the same mercy that God has towards our lives," he added.
"Brothers and sisters, on the Sunday of mercy > we remember with affection our beloved Pope Francis >. This memory is particularly alive among the employees and the faithful of Vatican City >, many of whom are present here, and I would like to thank for the service they carry out daily. To you, to us all, to the whole world, Pope Francis > addresses his embrace from Heaven >" he continued.
"We entrust ourselves to the Blessed Virgin Mary, to which He was so devotedly tied so much to choose to rest in the Basilica of Santa Maria Maggiore >. May she protect us, intercede for us, watch over the Church, support the path of humanity in peace and fraternity," she concluded.
"Only mercy creates a new world"
"We are called to the commitment to live our relations no longer according to the criteria of calculation or blinded by selfishness, but opening us to dialogue with the other," welcoming those we meet along the way and forgiving his weaknesses and errors." Thus Cardinal Pietro Parolin>, former Secretary of State, in the homily of the mass of the second day of the Novendials.
"Only mercy heals and creates a new world, extinguishing the fires of distrust, hatred and violence >: this is the great teaching of Pope Francis >", said Parolin >. "Memory > brings us back to the heart of faith" and reminds us, he added, "that we must not interpret our relationship with God and our being Church according to human or world categories".
The good news of the Gospel > is first of all "the discovery of being loved by a God who has bowed to compassion and tenderness for each of us regardless of our merits".
Mercy» also reminds us that our life is woven with mercy: we can rise up after our falls and look to the future only if we have someone who loves us without limits and forgives us."
